--- params: station: "Brighton Beach" title: "Brighton Beach" css: - ../quarto/index.css - ../quarto/nav_fixes.css format: html: grid: body-width: 900px page-layout: article theme: zephr code-fold: false toc: true toc-location: left toc-expand: true toc-depth: 3 editor_options: chunk_output_type: console --- ::: {.cell} ::: ::: {.cell} ::: Brighton Beach obtained a final score of 2.48 placing it number 59 out of 130. The remainder of this page steps through each factor listed below in no particular order. ::: {.callout-note icon="false"} ## Full Methodology The full methodology for how these scores are calculated and why they are important for consideration in upzoning is [available in the full report](../quarto/report_shiny.html). ::: :::{.graph} ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ## Service Frequency Service frequency is calculated as the mean number of services per hour in two time periods: - Between 7 and 10am towards Flinders Street, shown in blue. - Between 4 and 7pm away from Flinders Street, shown in green. :::{.graph} ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ::: column-margin The chart is also split by direction of travel, which in Melbourne's radial network is either towards or away from Flinders street. \ The mean values of these two periods are shown as dashed lines, and the mean of those two numbers is the final score. ::: \ The morning average freqency is 6.03, the average evening frequency is 6.41, which forms a mean score of **6.22**. ## Available Line Capacity ::: {.cell} ::: The chart below shows the average patronage on the Sandringham line(s) at the last stop before the CBD (Richmond). It is calculated for two times: - Between 7 and 10am towards Flinders Street, denoted as blue. - Between 4 and 7pm away from Flinders street, shown as green. :::{.graph} ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ::: column-margin The chart is also split by direction of travel, which in Melbourne's radial network is either towards or away from Flinders street. \ The mean values of these two periods are shown as dashed lines, and the mean of those two numbers is the final score. ::: \ The morning average patronage is 187.18, the average evening patronage is 280.91, which forms a mean score of **234.05.** ## Zoning Suitability The map below shows the properties within 1km of Brighton Beach that are suitable for upzoning in orange, with unsuitable properties in black. ::: column-margin Suitable properties are either neighbourhood residential or general residential and not under heritage restrictions. ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: \ Out of 1546 lots within 1000m radius of Brighton Beach, 1357 are suitable for upzoning. In terms of area, the most suitable properties cover **78**% of the total area. For more information, see the table below. :::{.graph} ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ## Existing Transport Infrastructure The map below shows tram routes and tram stops in green, as well as bus routes and bus stops in orange. ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: \ There are 0 tram stops in a 1km radius, with route(s) servicing the area. For buses, there are 20, with route(s) 922, 603, 923, 600. The data below shows the frequencies per route in both table and bar chart form. ::: panel-tabset ## Data ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ## Chart ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.cell .column-page layout-nrow="1"} ::: The final score for 'existing transport infrastructure' is computed by summing the average frequencies of each route and applying a weight to each mode. The current weights are intended to reflect the throughput each mode is capable of. At a minimum, trams can move twice as many people as buses at the same frequency, so trams are weighted twice as much as buses. The final score is **0.88**. ## Local Amenities The map below shows the local amenities near Brighton Beach within a 1000m radius. ::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"} ## Notes on Data Visualisation OpenStreetMap point locations were joined to polygon dwelling data for this visualisation. Some points could not be joined and are displayed as circles on the map. Some amenities are within the same building, e.g. multiple shops in shopping centres. In these cases, the building is assigned a colour corresponding to the most common amenity within it. ::: ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: \ The plot below shows the number of local services within a 1000m radius. Data is drawn from OpenStreetMaps classifications. Black dotted lines represent the means across all stations that meet the criteria for ranking. :::{.graph} ::: {.cell} ::: {.cell-output-display} ```{=html}
``` ::: ::: ::: \ Calculation of the final score for local services uses an index measure. It is described in more detail [in the full report](../quarto/report_shiny.html).. :::{.graph} ::: {.cell} ::: :::
